s a more expansive view. The study's overarching argument is that states' global environments and the particularities of their cultures, social structures, and political institutions often affect how they organize and prepare for war, and ultimately impact their effectiveness in battle. The creation of military power is only partially dependent on states' basic material and human assets. Wealth, technology, and human capital certainly matter for a country's ability to create military power, but equally important are the ways a state uses those resources, and this often depends on the political and social environment in which military activity takes place.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aArmed ForcesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMilitary art and sciencexHistoryy20th century. 0aMilitary readiness. 4aPolitics -- International Relations. 4aSecurity Studies -- Military Innovation and Transformation. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / International Relations / General.2bisacsh1 aAvant, Deborah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBensahel, Nora, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBiddle, Stephen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooks, Risa A., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrooks, Risa A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aFarrell, Theo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldman, Emily O., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHoyt, Timothy D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aReiter, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStanley, Elizabeth A., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9